Getting Started

Setup

Open 04-intro-to-r/01-ggplot2.R in RStudio if you’d like to follow along.

Tip

Before we get started, it’s a good idea to Restart R. That way nothing we did before carries through this section. (Session ➔ Restart R)

Setup

# Install packages
# install.packages("tidyverse")
# install.packages("tidytext")
# install.packages("wordcloud")
# install.packages("here")

# Load libraries
library(tidyverse)
library(tidytext)
library(wordcloud)
library(here)

Load the data

# Load data
load(here::here("materials", "workshop_data.RData"))

df <- df |>
  mutate(Branch = case_match(Branch,
                             "Disneyland_California" ~ "California",
                             "Disneyland_HongKong" ~ "Hong Kong",
                             "Disneyland_Paris" ~ "Paris")) |>
  rename("Park" = Branch)

Visualize the Data

Why Visualize?

  • Gives us a sense of the data
  • See the distribution of the data
  • Raise questions to explore
  • Help shape your process

Create a basic histogram

Create a basic histogram

ggplot(df, aes(x = Rating))

Create a basic histogram

ggplot(df, aes(x = Rating)) +
  geom_bar()

Create a basic histogram

ggplot(df, aes(x = Rating)) +
  geom_bar() +
  geom_bar(
    fill = "steelblue",
    color = "black"
  )

Create a basic histogram

ggplot(df, aes(x = Rating)) +
  geom_bar() +
  geom_bar(
    fill = "steelblue",
    color = "black"
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Ratings",
    x = "Rating",
    y = "Count"
  )

Reviews by year

What if we wanted to look at the park ratings over time? What would we need to do?

  • Make sure Year_Month is a date
  • Group by Park
  • Count ratings per year

Reviews by year

ratings_by_year <- df |> 
  mutate(Year = year(Year_Month),
         Month = month(Year_Month)) |> 
  group_by(Park) |> 
  count(Year) |> 
  rename(Ratings = n)

Sample the data

Look at one review

Brackets allow us to isolate a single cell.

df$Review_Text[11]
[1] "I went there with 2 daughters   1 y.o. and 4 y.o. Both of them were very excited. Little one liked most of the rides (the only one she didn't like was  It's a little world . It was too long for her. Older one was super happy to see the real princesses :)"

Convert it to a tibble

sample <- tibble(
  line = 1,
  text = df$Review_Text[11]
)
gt(sample)
line text
1 I went there with 2 daughters 1 y.o. and 4 y.o. Both of them were very excited. Little one liked most of the rides (the only one she didn't like was It's a little world . It was too long for her. Older one was super happy to see the real princesses :)

What is a tibble?

unnest_tokens

“I went there with 2 daughters 1 y.o and 4…”


sample |>
  unnest_tokens(word, text) |> 
  head(n = 10) |> 
  gt()
line word
1 i
1 went
1 there
1 with
1 2
1 daughters
1 1
1 y.o
1 and
1 4

Advantages of unnest_tokens

  • splits text into one word/token per row along with the original line number
  • takes care of converting to lowercase
  • removes punctuation

Process the data

Number each review

reviews <- df |>
  group_by(Park) |>
  mutate(linenumber = row_number()) |>
  ungroup() |>
  select(Park,
    linenumber,
    text = Review_Text
  ) |>
  arrange(
    Park,
    linenumber
  )

gt::gt(head(reviews, n = 3))
Park linenumber text
California 1 I ve previously been to 3 Disney Resorts. So I had my expectations sky high for the original park. And they were more than fulfilled. Even so it is a smaller park than many of its counterparts it had that magical feeling almost like you can ran into Walt itself when strolling trough main street. Reserve a day to get to know this park and some of its can not miss attractions like haunted mansion, pirates of the Caribbean, peter pans flight, space mountain, splash mountain and finish day with the astonishing paint the night parade.
California 2 I loved everything! :) It's the Happiest Place on Earth, you know?
California 3 I went there with 2 daughters 1 y.o. and 4 y.o. Both of them were very excited. Little one liked most of the rides (the only one she didn't like was It's a little world . It was too long for her. Older one was super happy to see the real princesses :)

Unnest Tokens

# Unnest tokens
tidy_reviews <- reviews |> 
  unnest_tokens(word, text)

gt(head(tidy_reviews))

California 1 i
California 1 ve
California 1 previously
California 1 been
California 1 to
California 1 3

Stop Words

gt(head(stop_words))
word lexicon
a SMART
a's SMART
able SMART
about SMART
above SMART
according SMART

anti_join

An anti_join return all rows from the left table where there are not matching values in the right table, keeping just columns from the left table.

Source

Remove stop words

# Unnest tokens and remove stop words
tidy_reviews <- tidy_reviews |>
  anti_join(stop_words)

gt(head(tidy_reviews))
Park linenumber word
California 1 ve
California 1 previously
California 1 3
California 1 disney
California 1 resorts
California 1 expectations

Word Clouds

Create a word cloud

set.seed(1234)

tidy_reviews |>
  count(word) |>
  with(wordcloud(word, 
                 n, 
                 max.words = 40,
                 colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2")))

What jumps out to you? How might we improve it?

Create a word cloud

Custom stop words

  • Stop word libraries are great starting points

  • Organization- or industry-specific terms may not be helpful

  • Custom stop word lists can filter these out


wc_removals <- c("day", "disney", "disneyland", "rides")

Word Cloud without Custom Stop Words

wc_removals <- c("day", "disney", "disneyland", "rides", "park")

tidy_reviews |>
  filter(!word %in% wc_removals) |>
  count(word) |>
  with(wordcloud(word, 
                 n, 
                 max.words = 50,
                 colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2")))
1
The %in% syntax allows you to look for a match inside a vector or column.

Word Cloud without Custom Stop Words

N-Grams

  • A continuous sequence of n words
  • Can be used ‘as is’, or run through a stemmer to get morphemes
  • Offers more context than single words

Set up bigrams

# Unnest into bigrams
tidy_bigrams <- reviews |> 
  unnest_tokens(bigram, 
                text, 
                token = "ngrams", 
                n = 2) |> 
  filter(!is.na(bigram))

gt(head(tidy_bigrams))
Park linenumber bigram
California 1 i ve
California 1 ve previously
California 1 previously been
California 1 been to
California 1 to 3
California 1 3 disney

Separate words

# Separate words
tidy_bigrams <- tidy_bigrams |>
  separate(bigram, 
           c("word1", 
             "word2"), 
           sep = " ")

gt(head(tidy_bigrams))
Park linenumber word1 word2
California 1 i ve
California 1 ve previously
California 1 previously been
California 1 been to
California 1 to 3
California 1 3 disney

Remove stop words

# Remove stop words
tidy_bigrams <- tidy_bigrams |>
  filter(!word1 %in% stop_words$word) |>
  filter(!word2 %in% stop_words$word)

gt(head(tidy_bigrams))
Park linenumber word1 word2
California 1 ve previously
California 1 3 disney
California 1 disney resorts
California 1 expectations sky
California 1 original park
California 1 magical feeling

Reunite terms

# Reunite terms
tidy_bigrams <- tidy_bigrams |>
  unite(bigram, word1, word2, sep = " ")

gt(head(tidy_bigrams))
Park linenumber bigram
California 1 ve previously
California 1 3 disney
California 1 disney resorts
California 1 expectations sky
California 1 original park
California 1 magical feeling

Word Frequencies

Total Words per Review

review_words <- tidy_reviews %>%
  count(Park, word, sort = TRUE)

total_words <- review_words %>% 
  group_by(Park) %>% 
  summarize(total = sum(n))

review_words <- left_join(review_words, total_words)

gt(head(review_words))
Park word n total
Paris park 439 18678
California park 368 17086
California disneyland 342 17086
Paris disney 332 18678
Paris rides 332 18678
California disney 322 17086

Review length by park

ggplot(review_words, 
       aes(n/total, 
           fill = Park)) +
  geom_histogram(show.legend = FALSE) +
  xlim(NA, 0.001) +
  facet_wrap(~ Park, 
             ncol = 1, 
             scales = "free_y") +
  theme_minimal()

Review length by park

TF-IDF

freq_by_rank <- review_words |> 
  group_by(Park) |> 
  mutate(rank = row_number(), 
         `term frequency` = n/total) |> 
  ungroup()

gt(head(freq_by_rank))
Park word n total rank term frequency
Paris park 439 18678 1 0.02350359
California park 368 17086 1 0.02153810
California disneyland 342 17086 2 0.02001639
Paris disney 332 18678 2 0.01777492
Paris rides 332 18678 3 0.01777492
California disney 322 17086 3 0.01884584

Plot TF-IDF

freq_by_rank |> 
  ggplot(aes(rank, 
             `term frequency`, 
             color = Park)) + 
  geom_line(size = 1.1, 
            alpha = 0.8, 
            show.legend = FALSE) + 
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  theme_minimal()

Bigram TF-IDF

tidy_bigrams |> 
  count(Park, bigram) |> 
  bind_tf_idf(bigram, Park, n) |> 
  arrange(desc(tf_idf)) |>

Sentiment analysis

Sentiment analysis

An introduction using the ‘joy’ sentiment.

# Get 'joy' sentiment
nrc_joy <- tidytext::get_sentiments("nrc")
nrc_joy <- nrc_joy |> 
  filter(sentiment == "joy")

gt(head(nrc_joy))
word sentiment
absolution joy
abundance joy
abundant joy
accolade joy
accompaniment joy
accomplish joy

Sentiment Analysis

# Most common 'joy' words in the reviews
tidy_reviews |>
  inner_join(nrc_joy) |>
  count(word, sort = TRUE) |> 
  head() |> 
  gt()
word n
food 321
fun 231
parade 187
love 139
magical 134
enjoy 114

Sentiment Analysis

tidy_reviews_sentiment <- tidy_reviews |>
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) |>
  count(Park, 
        index = linenumber %/% 80, 
        sentiment) |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = sentiment, 
              values_from = n, 
              values_fill = 0) |>
  mutate(sentiment = positive - negative)

gt(head(tidy_reviews_sentiment))
Park index negative positive sentiment
California 0 128 301 173
California 1 186 369 183
California 2 127 310 183
California 3 128 282 154
California 4 152 326 174
California 5 91 176 85

Sentiment Analysis

ggplot(tidy_reviews_sentiment, aes(index, sentiment, fill = Park)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ Park, ncol = 1, scales = "free_x") +
  labs(title = "Sentiment Analysis by Park") +
  theme_minimal()
